'Cangjie programming language_api_crypto_crypto_crypto_package': 'When using Cangjie Code API, The crypto package provides functionalities for generating secure random numbers.

For Linux operating systems, you can refer to the following methods:
If the system's package management tool supports the installation of the OpenSSL 3 development kit, you can install it in this way, and make sure that the system installation directory contains the libcrypto.so and libcrypto.so.3 dynamic library files, for example, on Ubuntu 22.04, you can use the sudo apt install libssl-dev command to install the libssl-dev toolkit;
If you can't install it through the above methods, you can download the OpenSSL 3.x.x source code to compile and install the package, and make sure that the installation directory contains the two dynamic library files libcrypto.so and libcrypto.so.3, and then you can choose one of the following methods to ensure that the system linker can find these files:
If OpenSSL is not installed on the system, you can choose to install it directly in the system path during installation.
Install in a custom directory and set the directory where these files are located to the environment variables LD_LIBRARY_PATH and LIBRARY_PATH.

For Windows operating systems, you can follow these steps:
Download the OpenSSL 3.x.x source code to compile and install the x64 architecture package, or download and install the third-party pre-compiled OpenSSL 3.x.x package for developers.
Make sure that the installation directory contains the libcrypto.dll.a (or libcrypto.lib), libcrypto-3-x64.dll libraries;
Set the directory path where libcrypto.dll.a (or libcrypto.lib) is located to the environment variable LIBRARY_PATH, and the directory path where libcrypto-3-x64.dll is located to the environment variable PATH.'

Code_Example:
import crypto.crypto.*
main() {
    let r = SecureRandom()
    for (_ in 0..10) {
        let flip = r.nextBool()
        println(flip)
    }
    return 0
}

'Cangjie programming language_api_crypto_crypto_digest_package': 'When using Cangjie Code API, The digest package provides common message digest algorithms, including MD5, SHA1, SHA224, SHA256, SHA384, SHA512, HMAC, and SM3.'

Code_Example:
//Call the general digest function provided by the Cangjie standard library
import crypto.digest.*
import std.convert.*
import std.crypto.digest.*
import encoding.hex.*
main() {
    var str: String = "helloworld"
    var md5Instance = MD5()
    var md: Array<Byte> = digest(md5Instance, str)
    var result: String = toHexString(md)
    println(result)
    return 0
}

//Call the MD5 member function
import crypto.digest.*
import std.convert.*
import std.crypto.digest.*
import encoding.hex.*
main() {
    var str: String = "helloworld"
    var md5Instance = MD5()
    md5Instance.write(str.toArray())
    var md: Array<Byte> = md5Instance.finish()
    var result: String = toHexString(md)
    println(result)
    return 0
}

'Cangjie programming language_api_crypto_crypto_keys_package': 'When using Cangjie Code API, The keys package provides asymmetric encryption and signature algorithms, including RSA and SM2 asymmetric encryption algorithms, as well as the ECDSA signature algorithm.'

Code_Example:
import crypto.keys.*
import crypto.digest.*
import std.io.*
import std.crypto.digest.*

main() {
    var rsaPri = RSAPrivateKey(2048)
    var rsaPub = RSAPublicKey(rsaPri)

    var str: String = "hello world, hello cangjie"
    var bas1 = ByteArrayStream()
    var bas2 = ByteArrayStream()
    var bas3 = ByteArrayStream()
    bas1.write(str.toArray())

    var encOpt = OAEPOption(SHA1(), SHA256())
    rsaPub.encrypt(bas1, bas2, padType: OAEP(encOpt))
    var encOpt2 = OAEPOption(SHA1(), SHA256())
    rsaPri.decrypt(bas2, bas3, padType: OAEP(encOpt2))

    var buf = Array<Byte>(str.size, item:0)
    bas3.read(buf)
    if (str.toArray() == buf){
        println("success")
    } else {
        println("fail")
    }
}
